nah Arendt, Anita Desai, Frantz Fanon, Albert Memmi, Primo Levi, Caryl Phillips, Philip Roth, Salman Rushdie, Edward Said, Zadie Smith, and Muriel Spark-as critical exemplars of the diasporic imagination. Against the discrete disciplinary thinking of the academy, he elaborates and argues for a new comparative approach across Jewish and postcolonial histories and literatures. And in so doing, Cheyette illuminates the ways in which histories and cultures can be imagined across national and communal boundaries.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aHolocaust, Jewish (1939-1945), in literature. 0aJewish literaturey20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aJewish literaturey21st centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aPostcolonialism in literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Jewish.2bisacsh1 aAméry, Jean, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFanon, Frantz, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aLevi, Primo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMemmi, Albert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRoth, Philip, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRushdie, Salman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSpark, Muriel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030009318640uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030019937640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300199376423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300199376/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY